                <h3>Understanding</h3>
                <h2>Hot Aisle Containment</h2>
                <p>
                    Hot Aisle Containment (HAC) is a system designed to isolate hot air within the return aisle and 
                    efficiently direct it back to the cooling units. This is typically achieved using aisle-end doors 
                    and vertical walls above the server cabinets. By preventing conditioned air from mixing with the 
                    warmer air, HAC ensures that only the hottest air is recirculated, thereby optimizing the cooling 
                    unit's performance. The ability to handle higher temperatures while maintaining efficiency is a key 
                    advantage of Hot Aisle Containment.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Additionally, a Hot Aisle Containment configuration effectively transforms the general 
                    working area into a cold aisle, improving the overall comfort of the environment. In data centers, 
                    HAC eliminates hot spots, reduces the need for extensive cooling hardware, allows for an increase 
                    in cooling setpoints, and can eliminate the requirement for additional humidity control.
                </p>
            </span>
        </div>
